        <bioghist id="ref8">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Edward Eliscu (1902-1998), was a lyricist (best known for 
                <title render="italic">Without a Song</title>), and also a playwright and screen-writer, and a progressive activist in the entertainment industry, notably in Hollywood in the 1930s and 1940s.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref9">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>The Papers contain: correspondence, unpublished lyrics, scripts and other literary writings (many of a political nature), copies of The Spectator, Eliscu's weekly column in the 
                <title render="italic">National Guardian</title>, film, theater and general political ephemera and internal documents, including from several progressive entertainment industry organizations such as the 
                <corpname>Hollywood League for Democratic Action</corpname>, the 
                <corpname>Hollywood Peace Forum</corpname>, the 
                <corpname>Hollywood Anti-Nazi League for the Defense of American Democracy</corpname>, the 
                <corpname>Hollywood Theatre Alliance</corpname>, the 
                <corpname>Hollywood Writers Mobilization</corpname>, and the 
                <corpname>Motion Picture Democratic Committee</corpname>. There is also a speech, written by Eliscu for delivery by Progressive Party candidate 
                <persname>Henry Wallace</persname>at an October 8, 1948 presidential campaign appearance in Portland, Oregon.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <arrangement id="ref10">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>The files are grouped into 1 series.</p>
            <p>Folders are arranged alphabetically.</p>
        </arrangement>
        <separatedmaterial id="ref33">
            <head>Separated Material</head>
            <p>Separated to the Library's NonPrint collection were a set of a dozen cartoons (Defending the WPA), and about a dozen photographs related to the campaign to defend blacklisted screenwriter Dalton Trumbo, and one photograph of Ann Meeropol.</p>
        </separatedmaterial>
